article.description:
Temeka Johnson scored a career-high 28
points to help No. 1 LSU earn at least a share of the Southeastern
Conference title Thursday with a 90-64 victory against Arkansas.
article.headline: 5-foot-3 Johnson has a career-high day
article.linkText: LSU earns at least share of team's first SEC title
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Temeka Johnson's value to LSU is far
greater than her stature.

The 5-foot-3 Johnson scored a career-high 28 points to help No.
1 LSU earn at least a share of the Southeastern Conference title
for the first time in school history, with a 90-64 win over
Arkansas on Thursday night.

"I'm happy I have this little one next to me on my team,"
Tigers coach Pokey Chatman said. "It's nice to have her leadership
on the floor."

Seimone Augustus slashed her way to 18 points and Scholanda
Hoston scored 16. LSU can wrap up an outright SEC crown at home
against Florida on Sunday.

LSU's sloppy play and some sharp long-range shooting by Arkansas
(15-11, 3-10) kept the game competitive in the first half. But the
Lady Razorbacks missed their first 17 shots in the second half as
LSU turned the contest into a blowout.

Johnson jump-started the Lady Tigers by running frenetic
fast-breaks and hitting shots on the run from all angles. She added
six assists and was 12-of-12 from the foul line.

Johnson said she didn't want to wait for an earful from Chatman
-- an All-American at LSU in 1991 -- to get the Lady Tigers rolling.

"When you're playing for a former All-American point guard, you
know you're going to hear it from her," Johnson said. "I figured
I should pick it up before she starts fussing."

LSU (26-1, 13-0 SEC) has won 13 in a row for the second time
this year.

After a 46-point LSU win in Baton Rouge on Jan. 20, Arkansas
kept close in the first half Thursday by hitting 5-of-6 from
3-point range. The Lady Razorbacks went on a 10-3 run late in the
first half to cut the LSU lead to 33-29.

LSU was up 37-31 at the half. Johnson said Chatman didn't fuss
at the team in the locker room, but did offer "some strong talk."

"You don't need to fuss, because they're so good at holding
themselves accountable," Chatman said.

Arkansas coach Susie Gardner said Johnson was sagging off the
Lady Razorbacks' perimeter shooters in the first half, and LSU
turned up the pressure in the second half. But mainly, Arkansas
just lost its range coming out of the break.

The Razorbacks were 5-of-6 from beyond the arc in the first 20
minutes, 5-of-17 in the second half. They missed eight straight
3-pointers while LSU went on a 24-2 run. It took 8:35 for Arkansas
to make its first field goal of the half.

Arkansas senior April Seggebruch, playing her final home game,
broke the drought with a 3-pointer and hit two more while Rochelle
Vaughn added seven points to lead a 13-2 Arkansas run that cut the
lead to 70-56, but it got no closer.

Danielle Allen led Arkansas with 13 points, including 9-of-10
from the foul line. Seggebruch, Vaughn and Kristin Peoples, who hit
four 3-pointers, each had 12.

Arkansas also couldn't handle LSU's tallest player, 6-5 Sylvia
Fowles.

She scored 11 points with five rebounds after taking a blow to
the head early in the game. She also blocked three shots and threw
off the Razorbacks' best inside players, 6-footers Allen and Sarah
Pfeifer, who combined to shoot 5-for-28.

"Sarah doesn't usually shoot 3-of-17," Gardner said. "That
has to do with Fowles' presence inside."
